12 ALLOW AGENCIES TO CREATE CONTINUOUS POSTINGS WITHOUT THE NEED
13 FOR OUTSIDE APPROVAL
14 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 126-14.3(3) reads as rewritten:
15 "(3) Require that a closing date shall be posted for each job opening, unless the
16 employing agency, department, office, board, commission, system, or
17 institution has approved an exception for critical classifications has been
18 approved by the State Human Resources Commission or as a special exception
19 through the Office of State Human Resources.classifications."
20 SECTION 4.(b) Unless the employing agency, department, office, board,
21 commission, system, or institution determines otherwise, exceptions for critical classifications
22 remain in effect if they were previously granted under G.S. 126-14.3(3) by the State Human
23 Resources Commission or the Office of State Human Resources.
24
25 GRANT EMPLOYING AGENCY FLEXIBILITY IN HIRING, PAY, AND
26 CLASSIFICATION
27 SECTION 5.(a) Article 1 of Chapter 126 of the General Statutes is amended by
28 adding a new section to read:
29 "§ 126-3.1. Employing agency flexibility.
30 (a) For the purposes of this section, an "employing agency" means the Council of State,
31 State agencies in the executive branch of government, the Community Colleges System Office,
32 and The University of North Carolina.
33 (b) An employing agency is granted flexibility, notwithstanding other provisions of this
34 Chapter, to do the following:
35 (1) Offer qualified applicants for employment the option to have their
36 applications considered for future positions at the same agency and at other
37 agencies within the same or comparable classification.
38 (2) Permit agencies to recruit and hire applicants from job postings that apply to
39 all vacancies in a particular classification across all State agencies.
40 (3) Classify or reclassify positions according to the State Human Resources
41 Commission (SHRC) classification system, provided employees meet the
42 minimum requirements for the classification.
43 (4) Establish employee salaries within SHRC-determined salary ranges for
44 respective position classifications.
45 (c) Nothing in this section diminishes the powers of the State Human Resources
46 Commission or the Director of the Office of State Human Resources under any other provision
47 of this Chapter or relating to corrective actions taken when an employing agency fails to comply
48 with this section."
49 SECTION 5.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
50
51 PERMANENT HIRING OF CERTAIN EMPLOYEES/SPECIFIC CONDITIONS
Senate Bill 124-Second Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 6.(a) Article 1 of Chapter 126 of the General Statutes is amended by
2 adding a new section to read:
3 "§ 126-6.4. Temp-to-perm hiring.
4 (a) The Council of State, the executive branch agencies, the Community Colleges System
5 Office, and The University of North Carolina may directly hire temporary employees into vacant
6 positions if all of the following conditions are met:
7 (1) The permanent position to be filled must be vacant.
8 (2) The temporary employee must have worked for a minimum of six months in
9 a substantially equivalent role with satisfactory performance. This six-month
10 period excludes any mandatory breaks required under G.S. 126-6.3.
11 (3) The temporary employee must meet the minimum education and experience
12 requirements established for the position classification, and the employee's
13 salary must be set within the approved classification range.
14 (4) The temporary employee must have been originally hired through the North
15 Carolina Office of State Human Resources Temporary Solutions Program or
16 directly hired by a State agency as a temporary State employee.
17 The Director of the Office of State Human Resources may waive the requirements specified
18 in subdivision (3) of this subsection, including both the minimum education and experience
19 requirements and the requirement that salary be set within the classification range.
20 (b) Unless otherwise provided, a hiring under this section is exempt from the provisions
21 of this Chapter, including any procedural or substantive requirements, including publicly posting
22 the position, requiring an application, holding an interview or new reference checks, selecting
23 the applicants from the pool of the most qualified persons, or following the priorities for certain
24 types of applicants under State law. This exemption for the hiring process does not affect whether
25 the position is subject to this Chapter once the employee is hired.
26 (c) A hiring under this section is not exempt from G.S. 126-14, 126-14.1, or 126-14.5 or
27 from Article 6 or 7 of this Chapter."
28 SECTION 6.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law.
29
30 ALLOW AGENCIES TO IMMEDIATELY HIRE ONE OF THE MOST QUALIFIED
31 CANDIDATES FROM A PREVIOUS POSTING
32 SECTION 7. Article 5 of Chapter 126 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
33 a new section to read:
34 "§ 126-14.3B. Hiring candidate from most qualified pool in previous posting.
35 (a) In addition to the authority granted by G.S. 126-3.1(b)(1), the Council of State, the
36 executive branch agencies, the Community Colleges System Office, and The University of North
37 Carolina are authorized to directly hire, without posting, into a vacant position so long as all of
38 the following conditions are met:
39 (1) That employer previously posted for recruitment, in accordance with
40 G.S. 126-7.1 and G.S. 126-14.3, a position that has the same or comparable
41 classification as the position that is now vacant.
42 (2) The person who is now being hired applied for that previous vacancy.
43 (3) The employer selected the person to be within the pool of the most qualified
44 persons for the previous vacancy, in accordance with G.S. 126-14.2, but did
45 not hire that person.
46 (4) For the position that is now vacant, the person who is now being hired meets
47 the minimum education and experience requirements for the classification and
48 has a salary set within the vacant position's classification range.
49 (b) Except as otherwise provided in this section, the hiring shall be exempt from this
50 Chapter, including any procedural or substantive requirements, such as publicly posting the
51 position, requiring a new application, holding a new interview or new reference checks, and
Page 4 Senate Bill 124-Second Edition

